pril 1277":"1230–april 1277","1230–1277":"1230–1277","1235–1261":"1235–1261","1259–Female":"1259–Overleden","1261–Male":"1261–Overleden","1210–Male":"1210–Overleden","1210–Female":"1210–Overleden","1259":"1259","1258":"1258","April 1277":"april 1277","1235":"1235","1233":"1233","1277":"1277","1210":"1210","before April 1261":"vóór april 1261","1230":"1230","1261":"1261","Great Torrington, Devonshire, England":"Great Torrington, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Kystemelbrig, Devon, England":"Devon, England","Great Torrington, Devon, England":"Great Torrington, Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"en":{"1230–April 1277":"1230–April 1277","1230–1277":"1230–1277","1235–1261":"1235–1261","1259–Female":"1259–Deceased","1261–Male":"1261–Deceased","1210–Male":"1210–Deceased","1210–Female":"1210–Deceased","1259":"1259","1258":"1258","April 1277":"April 1277","1235":"1235","1233":"1233","1277":"1277","1210":"1210","before April 1261":"before April 1261","1230":"1230","1261":"1261","Great Torrington, Devonshire, England":"Great Torrington, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Kystemelbrig, Devon, England":"Devon, England","Great Torrington, Devon, England":"Great Torrington, Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wyger","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from an Anglo-Norman French variant of <i>gaugeor</i> ‘gauger (official who measured liquids)’, or of <i>gag(e)ure</i> ‘bet, wager’. Compare   Gager  , though the evidence for that suggests more strongly an occupational name.","German (also <b>Wäger</b>), Swiss German, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): from Middle High German <i>wæger</i> ‘weigher’, German <i>Waager</i>, an occupational name for an official in charge of the city scales, responsible for weighing produce, especially produce offered as rent in kind, or for an official in charge of checking weights and measures used by merchants."],"variants":[{"name":"Wagemann","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erwin, Heinrich, Kurt.","German: occupational name for an inspector of weights and measures (see   Wager  ). Compare   Wagaman  ,   Wageman  , and   Wogoman  ."]},{"name":"Wagers","meanings":["English and German: variant of   Wager  ."]},{"name":"Wagar","meanings":["Altered form of German   Wager  ."]},{"name":"Gager","meanings":["English (Essex, Surrey): occupational name from Middle English, Old French <i>gauger</i> (Anglo-Norman French <i>gaugeour</i>) ‘one who measures or gauges’, specifically an exciseman who measured the depth of wine in barrels.","English: possibly a variant of   Wager  .","German: probably a topographic name from Tyrolean <i>Gagen</i> ‘alpine dairy hut’."]},{"name":"Weger","meanings":["German: variant of <b>Wäger</b> (see   Wager  )."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John Wyger was born in 1230, in Great Torrington, Devon, England, United Kingdom, his father, Thomas Wyger, was 20 and his mother, Elizabeth Joseph, was 20. He married Gundreda Peytevin in 1258, in Great Torrington, Devon, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in April 1277, at the age of 47."},"et":{"1230–April 1277":"1230–aprill 1277","1230–1277":"1230–1277","1235–1261":"1235–1261","1259–Female":"1259–Surnud","1261–Male":"1261–Surnud","1210–Male":"1210–Surnud","1210–Female":"1210–Surnud","1259":"1259","1258":"1258","April 1277":"aprill 1277","1235":"1235","1233":"1233","1277":"1277","1210":"1210","before April 1261":"enne aprilli 1261","1230":"1230","1261":"126